Source Oracle databases with very large SGA memory allocation can be more challenging to migrate to Cloud native database solutions. Large on-premise database servers can sometimes be configured with more RAM than what is supported for a single managed cloud database service. 

Source Oracle databases with SGA of over 512MB will sometime require "splitting up" to multiple target managed database instances, depending on the actual source workload.

DBMS_UTILITY is not natively supported in PostgreSQL. However, the orafce extension can be used to emulate a subset of common functions and packages, including some of the capabilities provided in DBMS_UTILITY but not all. For example, dbms_utility.format_call_stack is supported but not dbms_utility.format_error_stack.

Oracle BLOB Data Types are usually migrated to PostgreSQL BYTEA data types. The BYTEA data type:
1. Stores a LOB within the table limited to 1GB.
2. The storage is octal and supports non printable characters.
3. The input / output format is HEX.
4. Can be used to store a URL references to an AWS S3 objects used by the database.
2) Automatic refresh of Materialized Views require the creation of a trigger.

Oracle uses the XMLTYPE data type to store XML data. The XML data type in PostgreSQL can be used to store XML data. However, changes to application logic and SQL APIs will be required to ensure compatibility.

PostgreSQL 9.6 does not natively support declarative partitioning. Partitioning in PostgreSQL is implemented via "table inheritance". Each table partition is represented by a child table referenced to a single parent table.

PostgreSQL does not provide native support for sending email message from the database.
For alerting purposes, use the Event Notification Subscription feature to send email notifications to operators (Amazon SNS).
The only way to sent email messages from the database is via using AWS Lambda functions.
There is no PostgreSQL equivelant for restricting resource usage by certain workloads. Similar functionality can be emulated by seperating different applications to different database instances.

Querying data in remote databases in PostgreSQL is possible via two primary options:
1.Using the dblink database link function.
2.Using the postgresql_fdw (Foreign Data Wrapper, FDW) extension.
The Postgres foreign data wrapper extension is new to PostgreSQL and offers functionality that is similar to dblink. However, the Postgres foreign data wrapper aligns closer with the SQL standard and can provide improved performance.

The support for columnar storage in PostgreSQL isn't as robust as what is offered in Oracle.
In addition, the cstore_fdw extension is not supported in Amazon Aurora or RDS.

The support for columnar storage in PostgreSQL isn't as robust as what is offered in SQL Server.
In addition, the cstore_fdw extension is not supported in Amazon Aurora or RDS.

When migrating SQL Server databases to PostgreSQL, physical database backup/restore utilities cannot be used to replicate the data. Instead, logical replication solutions (such as Amazon DMS will be used. Databases with very high number of source tables< often require additional effort.

The full-text search engine provided by PostgreSQL is significantly less comprehensive compared to SQL Server.
Since full-text search in PostgreSQL uses a different paradigm and syntax and will most probably require rewriting the application.

PostgreSQL provides an extension for supporting temporal tables, but it's not supported by Amazon
Aurora or Amazon RDS. A workaround will be to create table triggers to update a custom history table to track changes on data

PostgreSQL does not provide a native Queue Mechanism similar to Service Broker. Third party queues with custom integration will be required to achieve similar functionality. Such as using Amazon Simple Queue Services. Read more.
Note that certain aspects of the queue/dequeue process will require to be migrated from the database tier to the application tier.
Currently, there is no equivalent in Aurora PostgreSQL for scheduling tasks but you can create scheduled AWS Lambda that will execute a stored procedure,
PostgreSQL does not provide an alternative to SQL Server FILESTREAM

The PostgreSQL CREATE SEQUENCE command is mostly compatible with the Oracle CREATE SEQUENCE command. Sequences in PostgreSQL serve the same purpose as in Oracle; they generate numeric identifiers automatically.

Usage of External Libraries in your Oracle database can complicate migration efforts. An External Library is a schema object associated with an operating-system shared library (often C code) which might contain business logic that will have to be manually converted.
MySQL triggers are associated with specific tables and fire at the row level, but not the statement level. Oracle system / event / database triggers are not supported in MySQL.

PostgreSQL provides support for two types of triggers:

1) DML triggers: triggers that fire based on table related events such as DML.
2) Event triggersL triggers that fire after certain database events such as running DDL commands.

Unlike Oracle database triggers, PostgreSQL triggers must call a function and do not support anonymous blocks of PL/pgSQL code as part of the trigger body. The user-supplied function is declared with no arguments and has a return type of trigger.

Cloud SQL for PostgreSQL supports both automatic and on-demand backups which are both incremental. They contain only data that has changed since the previous backup was taken. Backup data is stored in two regions for redundancy.

Usage of automatic refresh materialized views detected in the source database. PostgreSQL provides support for Materialized Views which are similar in behavior to Oracle with certain limitations, such as:

1) PostgreSQL Materialized Views can be refreshed either manually or using a job running the REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW command.
2) Automatic refresh of Materialized Views require the creation of a trigger.
3) PostgreSQL Materialized Views only support complete (full) refresh.


Because of these differences when compared to Oracle, some custom code or changes to the application logic may be required.
